<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAMESE SCOUTS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Apr 20  7:15:49 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
I knew a couple of Kit Carson scouts while serving in Vietnam.<br>
The first was named Loi. He hardly spoke English, and I hardly spoke Vietnamese. Yet, we each were well versed in the universal language of smiles and grins and laughter. Loi loved to laugh and make fun. My part in our &quot;relationship&quot; was that of the buffoon. <br><br>
My usual greeting to him was to fake seriousness with an exaggerrated, intimidating scowl on my face. I then would shake my fist at him and slowly drawl, &quot;You motherfucker.&quot; Thereupon, Loi, would squeal with laughter. We repeated this silliness everyday. It varied occasionally. Sometimes Loi would see me first and holler, &quot;Hey, Sergeant Motherfucker.&quot; I would then turn around, get that serious look on my face, and shake my fist at him. <br><br>
Another Kit Carson scout was named Thieu. He was much more quiet and subdued - not as playful. A good fellow and a good soldier. I was with him the last minutes of his life. Four of us carried his body in a poncho, through the tall grass, and placed it onto a chopper. A tearful Loi accompanied our fallen comrade. He would notify Thieu's family.<br><br>
Kit Carson scouts were former Viet Cong who came over to the American side - having been participants in the *chieu hoi* program.<br><br>
There is no doubt in my mind that if Loi survived the war until 1975, when the Communists overran the south, he would have been executed on the spot. They would have viewed him as a turncoat.<br><br>
So when I have the opportunity to converse, through cyberspace, with those Americans of Vietnamese descent, I have much to recall. Their's is a good heritage. I can only see good. I am unable to see evidence of a &quot;bad mistake&quot; in those who came here from Vietnam. I don't waste my time judging their individual circumstances as to why they came.<br><br>
Lien, take heart, and work hard. Your country needs you.
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


